When the American Empire finally went bankrupt, it left behind not only conflicts — but assets.
Vast assets.
An Everest-sized iceberg of shrink-wrapped inventory buried beneath deserts, glaciers, oceans, mountains, orbital platforms, and abandoned continuity bunkers.
The petrodollar — accepted by the world until the bitter end for lack of better stewards — financed acquisitions and endeavors of staggering scale and questionable necessity.
They had continuity plans for continuity plans.
Meals-ready-to-eat cached from Nevada to Alaska in preparation for continental migration events. Entire reserve cities sealed beneath salt flats. Autonomous factories still operational decades after the collapse.
One global disaster later, we — the Inventory Men — continue the work.
In cooperation with the United City States Union de Norte and the World Debt Fondholderbond, our mission is simple:
Locate. Catalogue. Scan. Reconcile.
Every tunnel. Every vault. Every forgotten depot.
